<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06308042 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06308042 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Drawing; DRAWING: Doug Griswold -- Mercury News (color)  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  US; ECONOMY; FORECAST; DECREASE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  ACROSS the country, Americans sense that the rules of the game have changed.They think that the rich prosper while the middle class sinks.;   They areright.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  THE MIDDLE-CLASS SQUEEZE  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  AMERICA -- What went wrong?  </MEMO><TEXT>     Home ownership has become an unattainable dream for 90 percent ofCalifornians, college expenses wipe out savings and life has become adesperate paycheck-to-paycheck treadmill for many.;   Why? People inWashington who wrote the complex tangle of rules by which the economy operateshave, over the last 20 years, rigged the game -- by design and default -- tofavor the privileged, the powerful and the influential. At the expense ofeveryone else.;   Reporters Donald L. Barlett and James B. Steele havecrisscrossed America the past two years, interviewing men and women who workin factories and offices, department stores and lumber mills, in nearly 50cities in 16 states and Mexico.;   Starting today in Perspective, Section C,and continuing in Section A of the Mercury News Monday through Wednesday, youcan read how the game was rigged against the middle class.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911103  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  DRAWING  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  180  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday, November 3, 199100308042,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENGFRONT  </LANGUAGE></DOC>